iddle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwilym ap Meurig was born about 1249, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Meurig ap Hywel, was -91 and his mother, Gwenllian Gwilym, was -99. He had at least 1 son with Cristen TURBERVILLE."},"et":{"Abt 1249–":"umbes 1249–Surnud","1249–Male":"1249–Surnud","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1253–Female":"1253–Surnud","1275–1326":"1275–1326","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1326":"1326","1249":"1249","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","Abt 1249":"umbes 1249","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1350":"1350","about 1275":"umbes 1275","of, , Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"Abt 1249–":"noin 1249–Kuollut","1249–Male":"1249–Kuollut","1364–Male":"1364–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1253–Female":"1253–Kuollut","1275–1326":"1275–1326","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1326":"1326","1249":"1249","1378":"1378","1376":"1376","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","Abt 1249":"noin 1249","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1350":"1350","about 1275":"noin 1275","of, , Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"Abt 1249–":"environ 